WEBVTT

00:01.174 --> 00:02.591
(bell ringing)

00:04.000 --> 00:10.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:13.386 --> 00:15.437
Too late. I saw them.

00:15.472 --> 00:17.189
Saw what?
Your free lunch tickets.

00:17.223 --> 00:18.223
Sucks being poor.

00:20.727 --> 00:23.345
Before the recession,
my mom was a real estate agent.

00:23.363 --> 00:24.363
Solid middle class.

00:24.397 --> 00:25.717
Now she's the only black waitress

00:25.718 --> 00:27.066
working at the Lima Country Club,

00:27.117 --> 00:28.617
taking orders from a bunch of

00:28.651 --> 00:30.519
rich old white guys who barely tip.

00:30.537 --> 00:32.296
And it kills me,
she's working extra shifts

00:32.298 --> 00:33.418
to pay for my dance lessons.

00:33.419 --> 00:35.624
Wait... you dance?

00:35.658 --> 00:36.938
Let's just keep that between us.

00:39.162 --> 00:41.547
Oh... young love.

00:41.581 --> 00:44.061
BLAINE: Do you remember when
you first started dating Santana

00:44.062 --> 00:45.102
and I started dating Kurt,

00:45.103 --> 00:48.703
back before everyone was
so busy and so... far away.

00:48.722 --> 00:50.539
Things were so much simpler.

00:50.557 --> 00:53.575
We had so much more hope and innocence.

00:53.610 --> 00:55.210
Every day was just like Valentine's Day.

00:55.211 --> 00:56.962
We're still young.

00:56.996 --> 00:59.064
Shouldn't we still be
experiencing those things?

01:00.650 --> 01:02.818
(bell ringing)

01:02.866 --> 01:05.716
<font color="#ec14bd">Sync & corrections by <font color="#FFA500">wilson0804</font></font>
<font color="#ec14bd">www.Addic7ed.com</font>

01:09.442 --> 01:10.776
Hey.

01:10.827 --> 01:12.060
Somebody slept late.

01:12.078 --> 01:13.746
It's lunchtime.

01:13.780 --> 01:15.564
Do you want a Croque Madame?

01:15.582 --> 01:17.750
We didn't go to bed till late.

01:17.784 --> 01:19.618
Thank God for earplugs.

01:19.669 --> 01:21.829
I love you both but I don't
want to hear any of that.

01:21.830 --> 01:23.622
We didn't do anything.

01:23.673 --> 01:27.926
He didn't even talk to me,
we just, like, laid there.

01:30.463 --> 01:32.131
I'm gonna take this down to the park

01:32.182 --> 01:33.748
and watch drug deals go down.

01:33.767 --> 01:36.084
It's good to see you again, Finn.

01:36.102 --> 01:37.102
You, too, little brother.

01:37.103 --> 01:39.772
Um, so, are you hungry?

01:39.806 --> 01:41.089
Can I make you some eggs?

01:41.107 --> 01:42.941
Yeah. Thanks.

01:45.528 --> 01:47.529
Wow, this place is awesome.

01:47.564 --> 01:49.865
It's not the ideal neighborhood, but

01:49.899 --> 01:52.701
at least we can sort of see Manhattan.

01:55.705 --> 01:57.623
I can't do this, Finn.

01:57.657 --> 01:59.657
I don't understand.
I don't know what's going on.

01:59.658 --> 02:02.611
Why are you here and why aren't
you in your uniform?

02:02.629 --> 02:04.997
Because I'm not in the Army.

02:05.048 --> 02:08.167
Well, I was, for 16 days...

02:08.217 --> 02:09.501
(Drill Sergeant yelling)

02:09.551 --> 02:10.886
FINN: <i>It wasn't that bad.</i>

02:10.919 --> 02:12.320
<i>I really felt like I was someplace.</i>

02:12.321 --> 02:13.361
<i>I could make a difference,</i>

02:13.362 --> 02:15.002
<i>and I'm pretty used to getting yelled at,</i>

02:15.003 --> 02:16.124
<i>so I was doing okay.</i>

02:16.142 --> 02:17.702
<i>Then, one day, I was cleaning Rachel...</i>

02:17.736 --> 02:19.296
<i>they make you give your rifle a name...</i>

02:19.297 --> 02:19.812
(gunshot)

02:19.846 --> 02:21.180
Right through my thigh.

02:21.231 --> 02:22.731
Thank God it didn't hit any bone.

02:22.765 --> 02:26.018
I got a semi-honorable
discharge.

02:26.069 --> 02:28.136
So I've been backpacking through Georgia

02:28.154 --> 02:29.638
for the past couple months.

02:29.656 --> 02:31.523
I'm sorry I didn't call you, but...

02:31.574 --> 02:33.158
but I was just so embarrassed.

02:33.193 --> 02:36.495
I mean, I left with

02:36.529 --> 02:38.847
so much certainty and confidence.

02:38.882 --> 02:42.100
I was gonna redeem my dad
and make you proud.

02:44.587 --> 02:46.821
I couldn't face you
seeing me as a Lima loser.

02:46.840 --> 02:50.158
Enough of this...
enough lumping around.

02:50.176 --> 02:51.710
All right, so what?

02:51.761 --> 02:52.827
The Army didn't work out.

02:52.846 --> 02:54.096
Plans change.

02:54.130 --> 02:57.599
You're here now, with me, in...

02:57.634 --> 03:00.152
in the greatest city in the whole world

03:00.186 --> 03:02.170
and what a better place for you and I

03:02.188 --> 03:03.605
to find you a new dream.

03:03.640 --> 03:05.607
Like what? Before the Army,

03:05.642 --> 03:08.510
you applied to Pace to be an actor.

03:08.528 --> 03:11.947
You know, that was obviously
not the right school but...

03:11.981 --> 03:13.866
I don't know, maybe NYADA is.

03:13.900 --> 03:15.850
I mean, why don't you come with me

03:15.869 --> 03:17.536
to all of my classes this week,

03:17.570 --> 03:19.688
and if you love it,
then you can move in here

03:19.706 --> 03:22.190
and we'll spend the whole
year just finding a way

03:22.208 --> 03:23.625
for you to get in.

03:25.995 --> 03:27.713
You serious?

03:29.666 --> 03:33.535
I love it here, but something
has always been missing.

03:33.553 --> 03:37.339
I let you go once and I'm not
gonna let it happen again.

03:41.144 --> 03:45.564
I mean, I'm not jealous,
I just think that it's insane

03:45.598 --> 03:47.159
that all Porcelain had to do

03:47.160 --> 03:48.600
to get an internship
with Vogue.com

03:48.651 --> 03:51.153
is take photos of every ridiculous outfit

03:51.187 --> 03:52.821
he's ever paired with a Cossack hat,

03:52.855 --> 03:54.239
and a see-through raincoat

03:54.274 --> 03:56.057
and then show up at an interview

03:56.075 --> 03:58.727
where he is lauded as a visionary

03:58.745 --> 04:00.985
because his jodhpurs happened
to match his riding crop.

04:00.986 --> 04:02.986
Well, you know, you could
follow your dream, too.

04:02.987 --> 04:04.467
Your mom gave you that money and said

04:04.468 --> 04:06.228
you could go to New York,
too, iyou wanted.

04:06.229 --> 04:07.189
I like being in college.

04:07.190 --> 04:09.254
My schedule is crazy but I love being

04:09.289 --> 04:11.911
a cheerleader and I like the idea that

04:11.912 --> 04:13.792
I'm never more than
a few hours away from you.

04:13.843 --> 04:15.243
Can't you do laundry at school?

04:15.261 --> 04:17.678
Mm-mm. My first week there,
I heard a rumor

04:17.714 --> 04:19.630
that all the water in Louisville

04:19.682 --> 04:22.083
is just purified runoff from
the Kentucky Derby stables.

04:22.101 --> 04:23.302
Nasty. But...

04:23.353 --> 04:24.970
mo importantly, I promised myself that

04:25.021 --> 04:26.921
I would only do laundry at home, that way,

04:26.940 --> 04:28.857
no matter how busy I got,
I would be forced

04:28.891 --> 04:31.092
to come home every few weeks,

04:31.110 --> 04:32.644
and then I'd get to see you.

04:36.115 --> 04:37.599
Are you okay?

04:37.617 --> 04:38.767
Yeah, sorry.

04:38.785 --> 04:40.770
I was up late last night,

04:40.771 --> 04:42.771
reading <i>Desecration:</i>
<i>Antichrist Takes the Throne.</i>

04:42.789 --> 04:44.773
It's the ninth book in
the Left Behind series

04:44.791 --> 04:47.793
of the apocalyptic Christian
novels about the end times

04:47.827 --> 04:50.945
and the rise of the Antichrist,
who name is Nicolae Carpathia,

04:50.964 --> 04:53.048
or Barack Obama, depending on who you ask.

04:53.082 --> 04:55.617
Brit, those Left Behind books
are really intense.

04:55.635 --> 04:57.285
What teacher is making you read those?

04:57.303 --> 04:59.120
And don't tell me that
Mr. Schue is doing

04:59.138 --> 05:00.806
Christian music week.

05:00.840 --> 05:03.058
It's not a class,
it's an after-school club

05:03.092 --> 05:06.895
that Sam and Joe and Kitty
and Dottie Kazatori are in.

05:06.929 --> 05:08.296
And you should come tomorrow.

05:08.314 --> 05:09.648
Who's Dottie Kazatori?

05:09.682 --> 05:11.066
She's Tina's assistant.

05:11.100 --> 05:14.302
Everyone graduated and things got weird.

05:14.320 --> 05:17.305
(school bell ringing, phone buzzing)

05:17.323 --> 05:19.307
Hey, stranger.

05:19.325 --> 05:21.743
(phone ringing) Hey. Uh...

05:21.778 --> 05:23.161
Crap! Can you hold on
one second?

05:24.864 --> 05:26.704
Isabelle Wright's office.
How can I help you?

05:26.705 --> 05:28.394
Um, it's me, Kurt.

05:28.395 --> 05:30.035
(phone ringing) Oh, my God, I'm so sorry.

05:30.086 --> 05:31.726
Uh, look, ve taken over Isabelle's phones

05:31.727 --> 05:33.647
